@page "/learn/pos"
@layout Consensus.Web.Components.Layout.MainLayout

<PageTitle>Proof of Stake · Tutorials · Consensus Lab</PageTitle>

<TutorialPage Title="Proof of Stake (PoS)"
              Lede="Skip the puzzles. Validators lock up money as a deposit, and the protocol picks one at random — weighted by how much they staked — to add the next block."
              Difficulty="Beginner"
              ReadTime="~10 min">

    <h2>The basic idea</h2>

    <p>
        Proof of Work asked computers to <em>burn</em> energy to prove they were serious about
        the network. Proof of Stake takes a different approach: instead of burning electricity,
        participants put their <em>own money</em> on the line.
    </p>

    <p>
        Anyone who wants to help validate transactions has to deposit a chunk of coins into a
        special on-chain account. This deposit is their <strong>stake</strong>. The protocol
        then picks a validator at random to propose the next block — but the lottery isn't
        fair: the bigger your stake, the higher your chance of being picked.
    </p>

    <div class="analogy">
        <strong>Analogy:</strong> Imagine a raffle where each ticket costs ₹100. If you buy 50
        tickets and your friend buys 5, you're 10× more likely to win that round than they
        are. PoS is that raffle — except the "prize" is the right to add the next block (and
        earn a small reward for it), and if you cheat, the protocol burns your tickets.
    </div>

    <h2>How a round works, step by step</h2>

    <MermaidDiagram Caption="A Proof-of-Stake round: weighted lottery + slashing.">
flowchart TD
    Start([New transactions arrive]) --> Stake[Validators have already<br/>deposited their stake]
    Stake --> Pick[Protocol runs a weighted<br/>lottery — bigger stake<br/>= higher chance]
    Pick --> Propose[Selected validator<br/>proposes a block]
    Propose --> Vote{Other validators<br/>verify the block}
    Vote -- "Looks good" --> Attest[Validators sign<br/>attestations]
    Vote -- "Looks invalid" --> Reject[Block rejected]
    Attest --> Finalize[Block added to chain]
    Reject --> Slash[Proposer's stake<br/>is slashed]
    Finalize --> Reward[Proposer earns<br/>a small reward]
    Reward --> Start
    Slash --> Start
    </MermaidDiagram>

    <h2>What "slashing" means</h2>

    <p>
        The key insight in PoS is that bad behaviour <em>costs the cheater money</em>. If a
        validator:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>proposes a fake or invalid block,</li>
        <li>signs two conflicting blocks at the same time, or</li>
        <li>vanishes from the network for too long,</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        … the protocol automatically destroys (or <strong>slashes</strong>) part of their stake.
        So while in PoW the deterrent is "you'll waste electricity for nothing", in PoS the
        deterrent is "you'll lose the money you put down". Both make attacks economically
        irrational, but PoS does it without burning energy.
    </p>

    <h2>The weighted lottery</h2>

    <p>
        How does the protocol pick a winner randomly while staying verifiable by everyone?
        It uses a special kind of random number generator called a <strong>VRF</strong>
        (Verifiable Random Function). Roughly:
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li>Every validator generates a random number tied to the block height.</li>
        <li>Whoever generated the lowest number, weighted by their stake, wins this slot.</li>
        <li>Anyone in the network can check that the winner's number is valid — no central
        coordinator needed.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>The real-world picture</h2>

    <p>
        <strong>Ethereum</strong> switched from PoW to PoS in September 2022 in an event called
        "The Merge". The change cut Ethereum's electricity use by roughly 99.95% overnight —
        from a country's worth of energy to a small office building's worth. Other PoS chains
        include <strong>Cardano</strong>, <strong>Polkadot</strong>,
        <strong>Solana</strong>, and <strong>Avalanche</strong>.
    </p>

    <h2>Strengths and trade-offs</h2>

    <div class="pro-con-grid">
        <div class="pro-card">
            <h4>✅ Strengths</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Tiny electricity footprint compared to PoW</li>
                <li>Faster block times — Ethereum produces a block every 12 seconds</li>
                <li>Slashing creates a strong financial deterrent against cheating</li>
                <li>Lower barrier to entry — no need for expensive mining hardware</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="con-card">
            <h4>⚠️ Trade-offs</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>"Rich get richer" — bigger stakes earn proportionally more rewards</li>
                <li>Less battle-tested than PoW (15 years vs ~3 years at scale)</li>
                <li>Big exchanges sometimes accumulate huge stakes, recentralizing power</li>
                <li>Complex to implement correctly — many subtle attack vectors</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>The "Nakamoto Coefficient" question</h2>

    <p>
        A common worry: what if a few wealthy participants own most of the stake? The
        <strong>Nakamoto Coefficient</strong> measures this — it's the minimum number of
        validators that would need to collude to control more than 50% of the stake.
    </p>

    <p>
        On Ethereum it's around 2 (just the two largest staking pools). On Bitcoin it's around
        4 (mining pools, not validators, but the same idea). A higher number is more
        decentralized. The simulator computes this for every PoS run — check it on the
        Specialized Analytics page after running a sim.
    </p>

    <div class="try-it">
        <h3>🎮 Try it in the simulator</h3>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-2">
            Start a PoS simulation with 10 nodes. Watch the leader distribution donut — it
            should look more even than a PoW run because the simulator gives every node equal
            "stake" by default. Compare the Gini coefficient between PoW and PoS runs.
        </MudText>
        <MudButton Variant="Variant.Filled" Color="Color.Primary"
                   EndIcon="@Icons.Material.Filled.PlayCircle"
                   Href="/simulations">Run a PoS simulation</MudButton>
        <MudButton Variant="Variant.Text" Color="Color.Primary"
                   EndIcon="@Icons.Material.Filled.QueryStats"
                   Href="/specialized-analytics">View PoS analytics</MudButton>
    </div>

